<rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world]]></title><link/> https://www.wsj.com/news/world <atom:link href="https://rsshub.app/wsj/en-us/world" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"></atom:link><description><![CDATA[WSJ - EN-US - world - Made with love by RSSHub(https://github.com/DIYgod/RSSHub)]]></description><generator> RS集线器</generator><webmaster>i@diygod.me (DIYgod)</webmaster><language> zh-cn</language><lastbuilddate> 2023 年 8 月 8 日星期二 21:55:41 GMT</lastbuilddate><ttl> 120 </ttl><item><title><![CDATA[Niger Junta Snubs U.S.-Backed Peace Mission]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>政变领导人拒绝欢迎旨在讨论回归文官政府的代表团，增加了地区战争的风险<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119036"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="560" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831613?width=860&amp;height=560" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">和平使团原定于周二抵达尼日尔首都尼亚美。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119036"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/drew-hinshaw" itemprop="url" rel="author">德鲁·欣肖</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/benoit-faucon" itemprop="url" rel="author">伯努瓦·福孔</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">更新于 2023 年 8 月 8 日下午 3:12（美国东部时间） </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-junta-snubs-u-s-backed-peace-mission-a79f76e5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>尼日尔新军政府周二拒绝允许美国支持的和平使团从邻国尼日利亚出发访问，称无法保证他们在首都的安全，首都的道路现在被民族主义青年封锁。</p><p>军政府对其他西非政府派出的代表团的冷落加剧了西非沿海文职政府与该地区内陆军事政权之间爆发战争的风险。</p><p>由尼日利亚前国家元首率领的代表团原定于周二抵达尼日尔首都尼亚美，距该国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-president-us-fumble-russia-africa-86cf1454-33d18bc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">总统卫队夺权</a>两周后。在那里，他们希望说服军政府领导人采取措施<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-leaders-detain-ministers-party-officials-6ba1efa1?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">恢复文官统治</a>，并防止与非洲人口最多的邻国尼日利亚<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/france-prepares-to-evacuate-european-citizens-from-coup-hit-niger-d46774af?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">发生武装冲突的风险</a>。</p><p>尼日利亚在西非国家经济共同体其他 10 个文职政府的支持下，威胁称，如果军政府领导人不下台，将使用武力推翻军政府。周四，尼日利亚将主办西非总统和外交部长紧急会议，讨论下一步行动。</p><p>尼日尔外交部表示，公众对尼日利亚试图扭转政变的愤怒将危及代表团的安全。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="480" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831650?width=700&amp;height=480" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一些尼日尔人对尼亚美军事政变表示支持。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>过去几天，成群的年轻人在连接尼亚美机场和首都的道路上以及通往总统府的大道上设置了路障，搜查汽车，并发誓要保卫国家。反对政变的居民表示，他们害怕抗议或表达自己的观点。</p><p> “我们这里有数百人 24 小时守卫，”在尼亚美中部守卫路障的支持政变武装分子易卜拉欣·纳迈瓦 (Ibrahim Namaiwa) 说。 “任何对士兵发动战争的人都必须先杀死我们。”</p><p>周一，尼日尔军政府欢迎来自布基纳法索和马里军事政权的代表团，这两个与莫斯科结盟的邻国誓言保卫尼日尔免受西非国家区域联盟西非经共体的干预。俄罗斯公开反对对尼日尔进行武装干预，其瓦格纳雇佣军组织表示愿意帮助军政府自卫。</p><p>瓦格纳领导人叶夫根尼·普里戈任（Yevgeny Prigozhin）在针对尼日尔新军政府领导人的音频消息中说：“请随时给我们打电话。”该消息于周二在与该组织相关的 Telegram 频道上分享。</p><p>支持西非经共体和平使命的美国在尼日尔拥有约 1,100 名士兵和数个无人机基地，直到上个月政变之前，尼日尔一直是美国在撒哈拉地区的顶级反恐伙伴。美国已花费约 5 亿美元建设尼日尔军队，其中包括价值 1.1 亿美元的阿加德兹无人机基地。</p><p>美国已与至少一名军政府高级成员进行会谈，以说服政变领导人回归民主统治。周一，代理副国务卿维多利亚·纽兰前往尼日尔会见军政府，试图通过外交手段解决紧张局势。</p><p> “这些谈话非常坦诚，有时也相当困难，”她告诉记者。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831616?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">西非国家和西方政府实施的金融制裁开始产生影响。尼亚美的一个市场。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：法新社/盖蒂图片社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>周二，尼日利亚官员试图压制有关军事干预的言论，但他们表示军事干预仍然是西非经共体的最后手段。</p><p>尼日利亚总统发言人阿朱里·恩格拉莱 (Ajuri Ngelale) 表示：“虽然西非经共体的谈判桌上没有任何选项，但没有任何投机性的猜测可以阻止正在进行的调解努力，以实现尼日尔共和国和平恢复民主统治。”</p><p>尼日利亚的文官政府——与塞内加尔、科特迪瓦和其他西非民主国家的文官政府一样——担心未能扭转尼日尔的政变将激励其他国家的军官夺取政权。就在过去三年里，马里发生了两次政变，布基纳法索又发生了两次政变，几内亚发生了一次，乍得又发生了一次。</p><p>更广泛地说，这个拥有 4.41 亿人口的地区正面临着青年人普遍失业、城市拥挤以及对未来繁荣的悲观预期的浪潮。基地组织和伊斯兰国盟友叛乱分子还在马里、布基纳法索以及尼日利亚和尼日尔发动了数千次袭击。</p><p>具有超凡魅力的军事统治者将自己视为技术官僚和亲西方文职政府的有吸引力的替代方案。 <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-coup-us-russia-africa-86cf1454?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">俄罗斯也填补了这一空缺</a>，为那些认为自己没有从与巴黎长达一个世纪的经济和政治关系中受益的前法国殖民地提供了自己的反殖民伙伴关系。</p><p>一些尼亚美居民表示，虽然他们最初并不支持政变，但他们认为军事统治比旨在恢复民主的武装冲突更好。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=7F7AB6E6-CE60-46D3-B0B7-C075C1006060&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fniger-junta-snubs-u-s-backed-peace-mission-a79f76e5&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption">尼日尔政变领导人宣布关闭其领空，导致全国各地的航班改道。与此同时，其他西非国家为军政府设定的周日最后期限已经过去。照片：Flightradar24.com<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“我没有呼吁发动政变，但既然政变已经发生，就应该允许尼日尔人民在不受外界干扰的情况下解决问题，”进口商奥马鲁·马拉姆·伊萨 (Umaru Malam Isa) 表示。 “虽然我不喜欢政变，但这可能是尼日尔实现发展的唯一途径。”</p><p>与此同时，政变的反对者表示，一波对政治领导人盟友的逮捕浪潮以及对最初的民主抗议活动的暴力镇压使他们无法发声，尽管西非经共体和西方政府实施的贸易和金融制裁已开始咬。尼亚美的一名医生表示，军政府冻结了除水电以外的其他支出，他担心药物很快就会耗尽。</p><p> “像我这样反对政变的人都不敢表达自己的观点，”医生说。 “只有一侧携带武器。”</p><p>写信给 Drew Hinshaw ( <a href="mailto:drew.hinshaw@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">drew.hinshaw@wsj.com)</a>和 Benoit Faucon ( <a href="mailto:benoit.faucon@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">benoit.faucon@wsj.com</a> )</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 19:12:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-junta-snubs-us-backed-peace-mission-a79f76e5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/niger-junta-snubs-us-backed-peace-mission-a79f76e5<author><![CDATA[Drew HinshawBenoit Faucon]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>国家/公共安全</category><category>叛乱</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>公安</category><category>叛乱</category><category>国际关系</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category><category>风险新闻</category><category>军事行动</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Latin American Countries Aim to Curb Amazon Deforestation]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>巴西总统接待地区领导人，因为雨林面临失去帮助抵消气候变化能力的风险<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831814/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="长期以来，亚马逊雨林吸收的碳多于释放的碳，但近 20% 的原始森林现已消失。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>长期以来，亚马逊雨林吸收的碳多于释放的碳，但近 20% 的原始森林现已消失。 UESLEI MARCELINO/路透社<span>UESLEI MARCELINO/路透社</span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119095"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001119095"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/samantha-pearson" itemprop="url" rel="author">萨曼莎·皮尔森</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/luciana-magalhaes" itemprop="url" rel="author">卢西亚娜·马加哈斯</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日下午 1:38 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/latin-american-countries-aim-to-curb-amazon-deforestation-c479cfd5"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>圣保罗——共享亚马逊雨林的拉丁美洲国家周二在巴西丛林城市贝伦举行了为期两天的会议，旨在制止<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazonian-destruction-risesbefore-brazil-presidential-election-11663166106?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">森林砍伐</a>，许多科学家指责森林砍伐加速了气候变化。</p><p>巴西拥有<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazil-battles-for-amazon-tribe-known-as-guardian-of-the-rainforest-5a66569d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">世界上 60% 的最大雨林</a>，该国为亚马逊其他地区的国家（秘鲁、哥伦比亚、玻利维亚、委内瑞拉、厄瓜多尔、圭亚那和苏里南）的总统和高级官员举行了会议。此次峰会是亚马逊合作条约组织 14 年来的首次峰会，该组织源于 1978 年亚马逊国家签署的一项条约，旨在促进该地区的和谐发展。法国驻巴西利亚大使代表法国负责管理南美洲东北部的法属圭亚那。</p><p>此次会议召开之际，巴西总统路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦寻求通过这项已有 45 年历史的条约，将巴西定位为全球反对森林砍伐的主要声音，并成为非洲大陆跨境环境合作的推动者。</p><p> “恢复和扩大这种合作从未如此紧迫——这是我们时代的挑战，”达席尔瓦在周二的开幕致辞中表示。</p><p>其他拥有大片热带森林的国家，如印度尼西亚、刚果共和国和刚果民主共和国，预计将与挪威和德国一起参加会议，这些国家为毁林计划做出了贡献。今年将在迪拜主办<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-a-e-names-oil-chief-to-run-cop28-climate-summit-11673542016?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">联合国气候峰会的</a>阿拉伯联合酋长国也将出席。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831850?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴西总统路易斯·伊纳西奥·卢拉·达席尔瓦在贝伦峰会上。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：安东尼奥·拉塞尔达/Shutterstock</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>亚马逊雨林的面积是印度的两倍，长期以来吸收的碳多于释放的碳，成为全球气候变化的重要制动因素。但随着近 20% 的原始森林消失，追踪森林的科学家们表示，亚马逊地区现在可能已经接近所谓的不可逆转的临界点，到了这个临界点，它就会干涸，最终变成稀树草原。影响可能是全球性的。气候科学家将森林丧失归咎于全球变暖，美国环境保护署表示，这解释了为什么热浪在美国等国家变得越来越普遍。</p><p>巴西国家空间研究所的初步数据显示，巴西亚马逊地区的森林砍伐达到自达席尔瓦一月上任以来四年来的最低水平，今年前六个月与去年同期相比下降了约34%研究，称为INPE。尽管达席尔瓦发誓要到 2030 年将丛林破坏降至零，但他认为，这一目标不能以牺牲巴西亚马逊地区约 3000 万居民的生计为代价。</p><p>达席尔瓦认为，巴西必须利用国外的融资和投资在亚马逊地区建立新的绿色经济，并发展受监管的碳市场。巴西依靠外国捐款来帮助其资金不足的环境执法机构运作，这些机构使用直升机、无人机和其他设备来监测广大地区的非法森林砍伐。</p><p>达席尔瓦在一份政府声明中表示：“我们想要告诉世界我们将如何处理我们的森林，以及世界必须采取哪些措施来帮助我们。”达席尔瓦表示，他计划向富裕国家施压，要求它们履行在<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/final-draft-of-global-climate-change-deal-is-complete-1449906731?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">2015年巴黎气候协议</a>中做出的承诺，每年提供1000亿美元帮助发展中国家应对气候变化。</p><p>包括哥伦比亚和秘鲁在内的其他拉丁美洲国家也制定了森林砍伐目标，但面临着非法采矿和贩毒团伙的严重挑战，这些团伙加强了对森林的控制，联合国最近将其称为“毒品森林砍伐”。</p><p>科学家表示，解决森林砍伐问题是南美洲面临的最紧迫任务之一。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831817?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一名巴西官员在检查巴西普拉卡斯的一家锯木厂。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：UESLEI MARCELINO/路透社</p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831819?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴西依靠外国捐款来帮助其资金不足的环境执法机构运作。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：《华尔街日报》的托马索·普罗蒂</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>INPE 研究员 Luciana Gatti 在 2021 年发表的一项研究显示，亚马逊东南部地区森林砍伐严重的地区已经不再发挥碳吸收器的作用，而是成为碳源。INPE 使用卫星跟踪森林砍伐情况。</p><p>丹尼尔·内普斯塔德说，亚马逊雨林影响着世界各地的天气模式，随着森林砍伐的加剧，这可能会使极端天气事件变得更加普遍。</p>他是加州地球创新研究所的负责人，在亚马逊工作了 30 多年。<p></p><p>内普斯塔德说：“森林是一个全球空调装置……一个影响世界各地天气的巨大热处理机器。”他补充说，所有领导人愿意开会讨论这个问题本身就是一个“非常积极的成果”。</p><p>今年， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/extreme-heat-waves-across-the-world-photos-7cc1544d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">致命的热浪</a>扰乱了美国、欧洲和亚洲大部分地区的日常生活，而南美洲冬季异常高温导致安第斯山脉的积雪融化。</p><p>环保人士表示，区域协调至关重要。在亚马逊深处，土著社区经常跨越边界，伐木者和犯罪团伙可以自由活动，一国的努力很容易因邻国的努力而变得无效。</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>是否采取了足够的措施来制止亚马逊地区的森林砍伐？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p>就在一年前，当达席尔瓦的右翼前任</p>贾尔·博尔索纳罗担任总统。博尔索纳罗开玩笑地称自己为“电锯船长”，他削减了环境执法资金，并对外国试图影响他对亚马逊的管理工作感到愤怒，尽管他呼吁外国<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/brazils-climate-overture-to-biden-pay-us-not-to-raze-amazon-11618997400?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">为砍伐森林活动提供资金</a>。<p></p><p>根据 INPE 的数据，在这位保守派领导人的领导下，四年内，一片比佛蒙特州还大的森林被毁。</p><p>政治学家表示，去年 10 月达席尔瓦的当选将南美大部分地区置于一群松散联盟的左翼领导人手中，从而缓和了有关亚马逊地区问题的区域谈判，而该问题从未产生过切实的合作。</p><p>诚然，参加贝伦峰会的国家之间存在着冲突点。</p><p>虽然达席尔瓦正在考虑开发亚马逊河口附近的海上石油资源，以帮助降低国内燃料成本，但他的哥伦比亚同行古斯塔沃·佩特罗上个月呼吁阻止该地区所有新的石油开发。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="467" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831860?width=700&amp;height=467" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">巴西里约热内卢州一家炼油厂附近的牛群正在吃草。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：佩德罗·普拉多/彭博新闻</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>“作为国家元首，我们必须确保亚马逊停止新的石油和天然气勘探，” <a href="https://www.miamiherald.com/opinion/op-ed/article277248923.html" target="_blank" class="icon none" rel="noopener">佩特罗上个月在《迈阿密先驱报》上写道</a>。 “即使我们正在解决国内的基本社会问题，但生活成本危机和猖獗的通货膨胀加剧了这些问题，我们也必须表现出勇气。”</p><p>巴西气候观测站的环保组织联盟负责人马西奥·阿斯特里尼表示，亚马逊流域国家可能会在保护土著社区、打击边境犯罪以及支持科学研究以更好地了解森林方面找到共同点。</p><p> “这些国家处于不同的政治局势……但他们都在议程中找到了同意这一点的空间，并聚在一起讨论这些敏感问题，”阿斯特里尼说。</p><p>不过，阿斯特里尼说，他们最大的共同点是希望让更富裕的国家帮助支付所有这些费用。</p><p> “给我钱——这是他们都会异口同声地说的一件事，”他说。</p><p>写信给 Samantha Pearson（ <a href="mailto:samantha.pearson@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">samantha.pearson@wsj.com）</a>和 Luciana Magalhaes（ <a href="mailto:luciana.magalhaes@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">luciana.magalhaes@wsj.com</a> ）</p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 17:38:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/latin-american-countries-aim-to-curb-amazon-deforestation-c479cfd5</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/latin-american-countries-aim-to-curb-amazon-deforestation-c479cfd5<author><![CDATA[Samantha PearsonLuciana Magalhaes]]></author><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>森林砍伐</category><category>全球/世界问题</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>卢西安娜·加蒂</category><category>丹尼尔·内普斯塔德</category><category>贾尔·博尔索纳罗</category><category>古斯塔沃·佩特罗</category><category>马西奥·阿斯特里尼</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>气候变化</category><category>国际关系</category><category>自然环境</category><category>砍伐森林</category><category>全球的</category><category>世界问题</category><category>政治</category><category>国内政治</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[A Famous Hippie Freetown Is Ganging Up on Drug Criminals]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>哥本哈根的克里斯蒂安尼亚街区吸引了大批游客和顽固的犯罪分子<figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831451/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="哥本哈根克里斯蒂安尼亚的居民动员起来，关闭了名为 Pusher Street 的露天大麻市场。" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption>哥本哈根克里斯蒂安尼亚的居民动员起来，关闭了名为 Pusher Street 的露天大麻市场。 <span></span></figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117853"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117853"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/sune-engel-rasmussen" itemprop="url" rel="author">Sune Engel Rasmussen</a></span> |詹纳斯·恩格尔 (Janus Engel) 为《华尔街日报》拍摄的照片</div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 8:06 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-famous-hippie-freetown-is-ganging-up-on-drug-criminals-6f630367"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p>哥本哈根——50 年来，丹麦首都克里斯蒂安尼亚 (Christiania) 是一个无政府主义、自由奔放的公社，因其露天大麻市场而享誉全球，吸引了来自世界各地的游客，同时还有顽固的犯罪分子和警方的定期镇压。</p><p>现在，一群居民奋起反抗控制了该行业的帮派，进行了一次危险的秘密行动，旨在关闭著名的普舍街。</p><p>近年来，有组织的犯罪分子将克里斯蒂安尼亚的大部分居民赶出了利润丰厚的大麻贸易，使北欧最大的旅游景点之一和丹麦宽容的象征变得恶化。</p><p>在发生一系列日益严重的暴力事件（包括几起杀戮）之后，许多居民已经受够了。周二黎明前，大约 50 名基督教徒（公社居民的称呼）在夜深人静时聚集在一起，观看他们订购的起重机使用集装箱和混凝土墙封锁普舍街的入口，几个小时后毒贩就会到达这里。开始一天的工作。</p><p>活动人士表示，“采取这一行动是希望将克里斯蒂安尼亚从帮派和铁杆犯罪分子的暴政中解放出来。”他们补充说，他们这样做是冒着自身安全的巨大风险的。 “我们都是普通人，必须去上班，为孩子们打包饭盒。这些团伙准备使用暴力并杀人，以保护他们的收入和领土。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831475?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">克里斯蒂安尼亚的许多居民担心封锁街道行动后几天内毒贩的报复。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>克里斯蒂安尼亚的居民和毒贩之间的对决是丹麦和欧洲毒品市场<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/how-peaceful-sweden-became-europes-gun-murder-capital-a5b500a7?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">日益扩大和暴力</a>的结果。这也标志着欧洲最激进、最持久的社会实验之一的转折点，该实验自 1971 年成立以来一直在违反法律的情况下生存下来，当时一群嬉皮士占领了一个废弃的军营，并建立了一个基于自我保护的反资本主义避风港。治理、自由思想和大麻合法化。</p><p> “我们需要真相时刻，”参与周二行动的一名居民说。 “我们已经从绿色能源、艺术、文化和 LGBTQ 权利的榜样，变成了我们所有的社区会议都在讨论 Pusher 街的暴力事件。”</p><p>克里斯蒂安尼亚早期的大麻贸易是由嬉皮士驾驶破旧的大众货车从亚洲运往哥本哈根推动的。如今，每年价值约 1.5 亿美元的大麻通过挤在 100 米长的鹅卵石步行街 Pusher 街的大约 30 个胶合板摊位流通。瑞典马尔默大学犯罪学副教授、克里斯蒂安尼亚问题专家 Kim Møller 表示，该行业约占丹麦大麻经济总量的三分之二，不过他补充说，没有人知道该业务的确切规模。</p><p>整个非洲大陆的大麻市场正在蓬勃发展。根据欧洲毒品和毒瘾监测中心的数据，2021 年，欧洲当局缉获了近 1,100 吨大麻脂和大麻草本，这是十年来的最高水平，这反映出其他更危险的麻醉品贸易的增加， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/police-raids-target-italian-mafia-across-europe-e4b5209d?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">尤其是可卡因</a>。根据 EMCDDA 的数据，在过去的十年中，欧洲查获的大麻的效力也显着增加， <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970203646004577213593506293770?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">长期成瘾的潜在危害也</a>随之增加。</p><p>贸易规模的不断扩大与克里斯蒂娜过去的生活格格不入。这个拥有约 850 名居民的社区坐落在丹麦首都一些最令人垂涎​​的房地产上，占地 34 公顷，距离议会大厦不到一英里。该公社禁止汽车通行，色彩缤纷、奇特的房屋、马厩和素食餐厅星罗棋布地分布在大湖泊周围，周围环绕着茂密的绿色植被。</p><p>弗勒尔·弗里隆德 (Fleur Frilund) 是一名 27 岁的文案学生，大约六年前搬到了克里斯蒂安尼亚，因为许多人建造和翻新了自己的房屋，她被这里亲近自然、拥抱艺术家、自由思想家和手工艺等古老美德所吸引。</p><p> “与栅栏另一边的大城市心态相比，这是一种完全不同的生活方式，”她在三楼的公寓里接受采访时说，该公寓以前属于一位海军上校。</p><p>居民们表示，他们正在努力挽救这种生活方式。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/71c21a2b-c71b-4263-8d14-cdebb8974f18.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>周日，即行动前两天，大约十几名活动人士在拉上窗帘的私人住宅里会面，以完成他们的作战计划。喝着咖啡，气氛有些紧张。没有人碰鹰嘴豆泥和新鲜出炉的面包。</p><p>一名中年男子的双手明显在颤抖。许多人担心手术后几天会遭到毒贩的报复。一名活动人士把他的妻子和孩子送走了一周。如果在行动中发生冲突，他们同意只有在出现武器时才报警。一名年轻的活动人士提议带上灭火器，以防毒贩放狗咬他们。</p><p>最终，黎明前的行动确保了当活动分子在克里斯蒂安尼亚周围移动时，没有毒贩与这些积极分子（无论男女老少）发生冲突，并在黑暗中引导集装箱就位。当年轻的参与者捣毁大麻摊位时，中年居民则在容器上喷漆：“普舍街已关闭。”</p><p> “基督教徒并没有反对免费大麻，”一位活动人士说。 “但是 Pusher Street 对免费哈希的事业没有任何帮助。这是免费大麻可能导致的最坏情况。” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831467?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">一幅壁画，描绘的是 2021 年 7 月被杀害的一名年轻克里斯蒂安尼亚居民。 </p></figcaption></figure></div><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831462?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Emmerick Warburg 自 1974 年以来一直居住在克里斯蒂安尼亚。</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>尽管克里斯蒂安尼亚起源于无政府主义，但它仍然坚持自己的规则，禁止汽车、毒品、摩托车帮徽章和防弹背心。在普舍街，和跑步一样，禁止拍照，因此毒贩可以知道警方何时进行突袭。</p><p>将居民驱逐出克里斯蒂安尼亚几乎是不可能的。据哥本哈根警方称，约有 40 至 50 名居民积极参与大麻贸易，与其他基督教徒一样，他们有权否决社区会议上提出的任何重大决定，并保护普舍街。</p><p>多年来，政府压力迫使克里斯蒂安尼亚逐渐放弃部分自治权。 2011年，在与国家进行了七年的谈判失败后，居民同意购买他们居住的土地，正式使他们的土地所有者地位合法化。他们一致拒绝单独购买房产，而是通过一个基金以约 1200 万美元的价格集体购买房产，并通过向公众出售股票筹集了部分资金。</p><p> “我们证明穷人也能够生活在市中心，”70 岁的埃默里克·瓦尔堡 (Emmerik Warburg) 说，他自 1974 年以来一直住在克里斯蒂安尼亚。</p><p>然而，几十年来，警方一直以普舍街为目标进行突袭，导致大量居民和经销商死亡。随着交易中的暴力事件不断恶化，警方每周都会对普舍街进行数次突击搜查，通常使用暴力手段，但结果却发现摊位重新竖起，隐藏的大麻一离开就从藏身之处重新出现。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bleed
"><iframe width="300" height="300" src="https://graphics.wsj.com/dynamic-inset-iframer/?url=https://asset.wsj.net/wsjnewsgraphics/projects/narrator/87f5a147-79bd-4611-aaf8-073d5a2f4872.json" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe></div><p>由于犯罪团伙在普舍街屡次发生冲突，弗里敦已成为丹麦最大的有组织犯罪团伙的战场。年轻外来者的涌入逐渐从克里斯蒂安尼亚自己的毒贩手中夺取了毒品市场的控制权。</p><p>一些团伙成员公然吸毒、携带武器、雇佣未成年人，这些行为都违反了公社的规定。</p><p>继前年一名年轻居民被杀后，去年一名年轻男子在摊位旁被枪杀，许多人感到不安。</p><p> “只要我们有朋友在那里，我们就能跟上，”在克里斯蒂安尼亚自治政府工作的瓦尔堡谈到普舍街时说道。 “他们违反了克里斯蒂安尼亚的道德准则。”</p><p>当局和克里斯蒂安尼亚互相指责对方在恢复秩序方面做得不够，但最近达成了一项罕见的合作协议。在 6 月的一次会议上，居民们与警方、司法部和哥本哈根市政府（该组织与这些当局已经争执了 50 年）达成一致，制定了一项最终清理普舍街的协议。</p><p>哥本哈根市长索菲·海斯托普·安德森 (Sophie Hæstorp Andersen) 表示：“普舍街周围的暴力和犯罪已经达到了我们既不能也不想接受的程度。”</p><p>活动人士并不抱有任何幻想，认为周二的行动将永久关闭普舍街，但他们表示，他们希望此举能邀请警方和政界人士认真尝试——即使这意味着毒品交易转移到了其他地区。哥本哈根，随之而来的是暴力。 “这是一个典型的毒品犯罪困境：暴力与消费，”犯罪学家莫勒说。 “如果你这样做，你就该死，如果你不这样做，你就该死。”</p><p>写信给 Sune Engel Rasmussen： <a href="mailto:sune.rasmussen@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">sune.rasmussen@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831470?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">从湖边看哥本哈根的克里斯蒂安尼亚。</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 12:06:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-known-hippie-freetown-is-ganging-up-on-drug-criminals-6f630367</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/a-known-hippie-freetown-is-ganging-up-on-drug-criminals-6f630367<author><![CDATA[Sune Engel Rasmussen]]></author><category>休闲/艺术/酒店</category><category>旅游</category><category>药物/物质使用/滥用</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>社会/社区</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>毒品贩运/交易</category><category>帮派</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>社会问题</category><category>贩运/走私</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>药品</category><category>物质使用</category><category>虐待</category><category>政治的</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>社会</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>合法举动</category><category>贩毒</category><category>交易</category><category>帮派</category><category>犯罪企业</category><category>社会问题</category><category>贩卖</category><category>走私</category><category>闲暇</category><category>艺术</category><category>款待</category><category>旅游</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[U.S.-Made Cluster Munitions Fuel Ukrainian Counteroffensive]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div>炸弹正在摧毁基辅军队艰难推进地区的俄罗斯战壕和炮兵系统<!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117870"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831501?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">乌克兰斯拉维扬斯克郊区的一艘集束炸弹运输车。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Michal Burza/Zuma Press </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117870"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline">作者： <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/ian-lovett" itemprop="url" rel="author">伊恩·洛维特</a></span>和<span class="author" itemprop="name">尼基塔·尼古拉连科</span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">美国东部时间 2023 年 8 月 8 日上午 7:23 </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p>乌克兰扎波罗热——在几周毫无进展之后，新交付的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-to-send-cluster-munitions-to-bolster-ukraines-fight-against-dug-in-russians-d2dd292f?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">美国制造的集束弹药</a>为乌克兰夺回被俄罗斯占领的领土的行动注入了新的动力。</p><p>乌克兰士兵表示，他们使用集束炸弹攻击集中的俄罗斯步兵、车辆群和其他目标，为地面进攻扫清道路。集束炸弹可发射数十颗较小的子炸弹，比普通炮弹能在更大范围内造成破坏。</p><p>面对广阔的雷区和莫斯科优越的空中力量，基辅的<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraines-stalled-offensive-puts-biden-in-uneasy-political-position-6f686ab5?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">反攻行动一直举步维艰</a>，这阻碍了利用西方提供的坦克和装甲车大规模攻击和突破俄罗斯军队的防线。</p><p>虽然集束炸弹本身不会使战场力量平衡决定性地向有利于乌克兰的方向倾斜，但士兵们表示，它们帮助他们<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ukraine-adopts-slow-approach-to-counteroffensive-our-problem-everywhere-is-the-sky-a2e51d7a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">重新夺回了他们一直难以到达的俄罗斯阵地</a>。</p><p>这些弹药加上战术的改变，使乌克兰军队能够在某些地方推进到俄罗斯主要防线的打击距离内。这一进展伴随着巨大的伤亡。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=EDA02BF5-0836-4277-AB7C-10442F70192F&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-s-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> 《华尔街日报》解释了集束弹药背后的技术以及它们为何引起人道主义担忧。插图：雅各布·亚历山大·尼尔森<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p>“集束炸弹很好。他们是有效的，”侦察连连长阿纳托利·哈琴科上尉说。 “但俄罗斯人挖得很深，而且学得很快。”</p><p>哈琴科说，俄罗斯的战壕可能有7英尺深，俄罗斯人正在通过更分散的兵力来适应，以避免重大损失。</p><p>最近扎波罗热市东南部Robobyne村周围的战斗证明了乌克兰军火库中新武器的有效性。</p><p> 7月下旬，一个排被困在村庄东边，遭受了俄罗斯的猛烈炮火。该部队通过无线电向指挥官发出请求，要求撤退。他告诉排要躲起来。集束炸弹飞过头顶。一名士兵说，他听到了类似下雨的声音，随后俄罗斯广播频道出现混乱。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="1262" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/ad8ecb39-26bb-4a4d-b98b-c4700b367059-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> “他们大喊，‘我们有很多伤员。我们需要撤离。我们正在撤退，”乌克兰士兵说道。士兵们说，该排向前推进，占领了俄罗斯阵地。</p><p>乌克兰仍然没有达到俄罗斯最强大的防御、一系列战壕、坦克陷阱和其他障碍。军事专家表示，乌克兰可能需要<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/german-made-leopard-tanks-for-ukraine-are-politically-symbolic-but-no-game-changer-11674151572?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">豹2坦克</a>和其他西方提供的装甲车来突破这些防线。</p><p>为了保护这些车辆，乌克兰军方改变了策略，因为六月初乌克兰军队在雷区大量损失了这些车辆。现在，步兵在其他部队调来的预备队的支持下，正在步行穿过雷区，带领前进。</p><p>士兵们表示，随着战略变化，乌克兰军队现在相信他们有机会取得突破。 </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          inline
"><img width="600" height="2770" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/16d21f69-0148-4de6-8efa-d7313e2e8cf8-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p>上周，33 岁的步兵列兵亚历山大 (Oleksandr) 的 16 人排向俄罗斯阵地推进，遭到俄罗斯机枪的猛烈射击。乌克兰人被迫撤退。</p><p>然后乌克兰用集束弹药击中了隐藏俄罗斯军队的林木线。灌木丛和草着火了。当下一次攻击开始时，亚历山大可以看到他正在射击的俄罗斯人，他们不再隐藏在灌木丛中。</p><p>他的排占领了该阵地，杀死了大约 12 名俄罗斯人，并俘虏了另外几人。他说，囚犯们因集束炸弹而遭受脑震荡和烧伤。</p><p>他说：“使用集束炸弹，发射三枪，树木就会完全倒塌。”他补充说，集束炸弹袭击后，来袭的火力减少了。他说，由于这些弹药会造成大范围的破坏，因此它们不需要那么准确才能有效。</p><p> “即使你错过了一点，它仍然有效，”他说。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831503?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent">收集了去年袭击乌克兰哈尔科夫的俄罗斯火箭碎片，包括集束弹。</p><p class="imageCredit">照片：Libkos/美联社</p></figcaption></figure></div><p>美国驻欧洲陆军前司令本·霍奇斯中将表示，美国发送的是集束弹药，而不是更多的榴弹炮弹药，而<a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-ramps-up-howitzer-shell-production-to-supply-ukraine-replenish-stockpiles-1e6dce54?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">西方国家的榴弹炮弹药已经不足</a>。他预计集束炸弹会更有效。它们是为一支寡不敌众的军队而设计的，就像现在的乌克兰一样。</p><p> “对付大规模编队的部分方法就是使用这种可分散的弹药，”他说。 “如果你坐在露天战壕中，你将为这些事情付出巨大的代价。”</p><p>最近发布在社交媒体上的视频显示，乌克兰集束弹药袭击后，俄罗斯士兵身上有六处小伤。霍奇斯表示，这些炸弹也符合他所认为的乌克兰针对俄罗斯火炮的战略转变。</p><p>他说：“只要炮兵能够到达，这些炮弹就能真正摧毁它们。”</p><p>这些武器被100多个国家禁止，美国向乌克兰运送这些武器的决定受到了人道主义组织的严厉批评。并非所有的小炸弹都会立即爆炸，有时它们还会伤害多年后遇到的人。</p><p> Russian forces have been using cluster munitions throughout the war: The white shell casings that carry them stick out of fields around the country. Ukraine also used them at times last year, according to a United Nations report. </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"><img width="600" height="610" src="https://s.wsj.net/public/resources/images/b0723491-abf8-41f3-aadf-419194652de4-fallback_app.jpg" alt="不明确的" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><p> A soldier in an artillery unit who has fired the cluster munitions said they were most effective in fields, where they dispersed over a wider area.</p><p> “Cluster munitions are important, but they&#39;re not a turning point,” he said, adding that it was important to have different kinds of artillery for different situations.</p><p> Usually, infantrymen said, artillery units fire a mix of different munitions at a Russian position before they advance on foot. Still, the human cost of the progress around Robotyne has been steep.</p><p> “We&#39;re demining the fields with bodies,” said a platoon commander from another of the newly formed, Western-trained brigades. “It&#39;s awful.”</p><p> Oleksandr Pershin, an infantryman, said that in the fields east of Robotyne, the ability of cluster munitions to wipe out tree cover was invaluable. During a recent assault on a Russian position, he said, there was no tree left above waist height.</p><p> “Everything else was destroyed,” he said, “mostly from the cluster munitions.”</p><p> Once his unit had taken that position, he said, they tried to keep pushing through the trees toward the next Russian line. For 24 hours, they made a series of assaults but kept getting pushed back, as the Russians sprayed them with machine-gun fire.</p><p> Eventually, they were ordered to dig trenches where they were.</p><p> While Pershin, 34, was digging, a rocket landed near him, spraying him with shrapnel and sending him to the hospital. As he spoke, his arm was in a sling and bandages covered wounds all over his body. Of 60 men in the assault, he said, 45 had been injured or killed. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=A74E51B6-FB53-4840-BB4D-2B1A0CCC986B&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fu-s-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> At least seven people were killed and over 80 injured in a Russian attack on the town of Pokrovsk on Monday, officials said. The strikes damaged apartments, a hotel, restaurants, shops and administrative buildings. Photo: Viacheslav Ratynskyi/Reuters<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div><p class="articleTagLine">—James Marson contributed to this article.</p><p> Write to Ian Lovett at <a href="mailto:ian.lovett@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">ian.lovett@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:23:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/us-made-cluster-munitions-fuel-ukrainian-counteroffensive-c45c305f<author><![CDATA[Ian Lovett]]></author><category> gfx-contrib</category><category> ukraine</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>National/Public Security</category><category> Armed Forces</category><category> Risk News</category><category> Military Action</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> political</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>public security</category><category> armed forces</category><category> risk news</category><category> military action </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Dozens Die in China Floods as Typhoon Remnants Batter North]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Nearly two weeks after making landfall, Doksuri still wreaks mayhem—and another storm is coming <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117838"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=6B5B836E-22CB-4333-B82F-35159829AF0D&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Fdozens-die-in-china-floods-as-typhoon-remnants-batter-north-aeeb7d69&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> Millions of people were displaced as record-breaking rainfall inundated Jilin province in northeastern China. The heavy rains were remnants of Typhoon Doksuri that had earlier flooded the Beijing area. Photo: Yan Linyun/Zuma Press<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117838"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/selina-cheng" itemprop="url" rel="author">Selina Cheng</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 8, 2023 7:21 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/dozens-die-in-china-floods-as-typhoon-remnants-batter-north-aeeb7d69"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> HONG KONG—Dozens of people died and millions more have been displaced after the remnants of Typhoon Doksuri battered China&#39;s northeast, dumping torrential rain and causing widespread flooding, according to local governments and state media.</p><p> The northeastern provinces of Jilin and Heilongjiang were the latest to feel the aftereffects from <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/beijing-area-hit-by-deadliest-flooding-in-a-decade-73c571fc?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">a storm that made landfall</a> nearly two weeks ago in Fujian, about 2,000 miles to the south. Beijing and the nearby major port city of Tianjin, as well as surrounding regions continued to suffer the aftermath from days of heavy rainfall, even though the weather in the Chinese capital on Tuesday was partly sunny—with no rain.</p><p> Millions of people living across swaths of China still face the risk of flooding from the heavy precipitation dumped by Doksuri as it ground north. A second typhoon, Khanun, is now threatening China&#39;s northeast after making a zigzag to briefly menace Japan. Khanun is forecast to hit the Korean Peninsula in the coming days.</p><p> China&#39;s typically arid northeast may again expect torrential rain this weekend, after accumulating more than 100 millimeters, around 4 inches, of rainfall in some areas over five days last week, China&#39;s meteorological service said. That is more than a fifth of the annual average for Heilongjiang <strong>&nbsp;</strong> province. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831431?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A man wading through a flooded farm in China&#39;s Hebei province.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: TINGSHU WANG/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Rising waters have been putting a strain on embankments and flood basins of the Songhua and Nen rivers in the northeast, the Ministry of Emergency Management said in a statement Monday. The arrival of Khanun is expected to make rescue efforts more difficult, it said.</p><p> The central government has yet to release nationwide figures for the total number of people who have died, gone missing or have been displaced, 10 days after hundreds of counties and towns were submerged by the floods.</p><p> In Jilin, 14 people died, including three local officials, authorities said on social media Sunday. Another official was missing. Around 100,000 people from one town were affected by the floods. Four reservoirs in the area continued discharging to maintain safe water levels, the local government said in a social-media post.</p><p> Heilongjiang, a major food-producing province, saw 160,000 people displaced and around 220,000 acres of agricultural land affected, the People&#39;s Daily reported Sunday.</p><p> Areas further south and surrounding Beijing and Hebei, an industrial province southwest near Beijing, were among the earliest to face the effects of the typhoon. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831428?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Millions of people in Hebei province have been affected by the downpours.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: TINGSHU WANG/REUTERS</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> As the recent heavy rains feed into river systems, the port-city of Tianjin is bracing for floods by Wednesday even though the weather there has cleared, state media reported earlier. Around 80,000 people have been evacuated from their homes, the city&#39;s Bureau of Emergency Management reported Sunday.</p><p> Ten people from Hebei died and 18 were missing as of Saturday <strong>,</strong> according to state media.</p><p> Zhuozhou, in Hebei, was hit particularly hard. More than 130,000 of its 600,000 population were affected, state media reported last week.</p><p> The flooding also hit some manufacturing. Shenzhen-listed Aerospace Hi-Tech Holding Group said one of its factories in Zhuozhou&#39;s aeronautics industrial park suspended production because its equipment was underwater.</p><p> Around 3.4 million people from over 100 counties in Hebei province were affected by the downpours, including about 1.7 million people who were displaced as of Monday, according to state media. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831430?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Debris clogged a street on the outskirts of Beijing on Monday.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Andy Wong/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> As millions struggled to cope with the floods, a Hebei official drew public criticism after saying that the province should act as Beijing&#39;s buffer by holding water in its basins to reduce the strain on the capital.</p><p> State media reports and local government social-media releases focused on rescue and restoration efforts, giving detailed accounts of emergency supplies deployed. Reports by state-owned news agency Xinhua tallied the equipment deployed for the rescue mission in Zhuozhou, such as generators and trucks carrying drinking water.</p><p> Tens of thousands of troops from China&#39;s People&#39;s Liberation Army and paramilitary police were also deployed in the rescue efforts near Beijing, repairing roads and clearing riverbanks, the agency reported.</p><p> The social-media account for the government of Jilin published the number of households where electricity was restored, lamp posts that were repaired and packets of medication dropped from helicopters.</p><p> Write to Selina Cheng at <a href="mailto:selina.cheng@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">selina.cheng@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:21:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/dozens-die-in-china-floods-as-typhoon-remnants-batter-north-aeeb7d69</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/dozens-die-in-china-floods-as-typhoon-remnants-batter-north-aeeb7d69<author><![CDATA[Selina Cheng]]></author><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Disasters/Accidents</category><category> Floods/Tidal Waves</category><category>飓风/台风</category><category>风暴</category><category>Natural Disasters</category><category>政治/国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>Regional Politics</category><category> Risk News</category><category> Weather</category><category> SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> political</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>灾难</category><category>accidents</category><category>洪水</category><category>tidal waves</category><category>飓风</category><category>台风</category><category>storms</category><category> natural disasters</category><category>政治</category><category>国际关系</category><category>国内政治</category><category>regional politics</category><category> risk news</category><category>天气</category><category>媒体</category><category>entertainment </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[China Drafts Rules for Facial-Recognition Use]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Authorities propose limits on when to use the technology, even as they leave national-security exceptions <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117836"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          header
"><figure class="media-object-image img-header"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="860" height="573" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831488?width=860&amp;height=573" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Facial-recognition use in China has been expanding in recent years.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Qilai Shen/Bloomberg News </p></figcaption></figure></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001117836"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/karen-hao" itemprop="url" rel="author">Karen Hao</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/liza-lin" itemprop="url" rel="author">Liza Lin</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 8, 2023 7:07 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-drafts-rules-for-facial-recognition-use-4953506e"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> China released draft rules on Tuesday to curb uses of facial recognition, taking a step to limit the expansion of a polarizing technology while leaving large carve outs for national-security-related uses.</p><p> The draft from the internet regulator, the Cybersecurity Administration of China, proposes to restrict <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/facial-recognition-goes-mainstream-1537322700?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the use of the technology</a> to instances where it has a specific purpose and is sufficiently necessary. The rules also ban the use of the technology for identifying race, ethnicity, religious belief or health status—applications that haven&#39;t been scientifically proven—unless a person has given consent or for the purposes of national security.</p><p> The stipulations bring China&#39;s stance on private and commercial uses of facial recognition closer to Western norms, including rules proposed in the European Union and by local governments in the US It also leaves exceptions for national-security-related uses of the technology, a common feature among <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-lays-out-strict-rules-for-chatgpt-like-ai-tools-32f70c89?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">China&#39;s data and security regulations</a> .</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> “Within one law you have provisions that reflect an authoritarian tech-enabled superpower and also genuine concern about misuse of the technology,” said Samm Sacks, a senior fellow at Yale Law School&#39;s Paul Tsai China Center. “That&#39;s the sweet and sour approach of Chinese governance.”</p><p> The proposal is the latest in a series of moves by China&#39;s government to put guardrails around how companies use data and artificial intelligence, putting it at the forefront of global attempts to regulate cutting-edge technology. <strong>&nbsp;</strong></p><p> Earlier this year, the regulator <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-a-pioneer-in-regulating-algorithms-turns-its-focus-to-deepfakes-11673149283?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">implemented rules</a> on so-called deepfakes, AI-generated media, and proposed others on generative AI tools similar to OpenAI&#39;s ChatGPT. Last year, it began <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-blazes-hazy-new-trail-to-tame-internets-algorithms-11661866321?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">regulating the algorithms</a> that underpin popular apps and internet platforms including TikTok&#39;s Chinese equivalent Douyin and the ubiquitous super app <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TCEHY" class="">WeChat</a> <span class="company-name-type">.</span></p><p> There is no national law regulating the use of facial recognition in the US, even though some states including Massachusetts and cities such as San Francisco <strong>&nbsp;</strong> have imposed limits, particularly with regard to law enforcement&#39;s use of the technology. In Europe, policy makers recently agreed on a draft version of a law governing artificial intelligence, which will ban the use of real-time facial recognition in public spaces by police and other state security forces.</p><p> The Chinese rules also come after China&#39;s Covid controls led to the blanket adoption of location logging and access-control technologies. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831490?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> China has begun regulating the algorithms that underpin popular apps such as TikTok&#39;s Chinese equivalent Douyin.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Andrea Verdelli/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Graham Webster, a research scholar who heads the Stanford University-based DigiChina Project that examines China&#39;s digital-policy developments, said the draft seems aimed at discouraging unnecessary use of facial recognition. “If enforced, it would cool the proliferation of biometric gadgetry outside security contexts,” he said.</p><p> Facial-recognition use in China has been burgeoning over the past seven years, with the means to use your face as a form of identity mushrooming in malls, office buildings, airports and hotels. Chinese consumers can opt to use their faces to pay for items in some stores, enter buildings and for identity checks before boarding a plane.</p><p> Surveillance cameras are ubiquitous in many Chinese cities, and some of China&#39;s largest facial-recognition suppliers have partnerships with local police to provide the technology for security purposes—tracking not just criminals but also dissidents, ethnic minorities and others the government sees as threatening national security.</p><p> Such technology is at the heart of international criticism of Beijing for its treatment of ethnic minority groups in the northwestern region of Xinjiang, where the Chinese government has carried out a campaign of forced ethnic assimilation targeting Turkic Muslims. Authorities in Xinjiang have used facial recognition and other surveillance tools to track and sort Muslims, sending hundreds of thousands to internment camps for political indoctrination, according to researchers. China has rejected those allegations, referring to its policies in Xinjiang as a campaign to prevent terrorism.</p><p> Many people in China greeted the initial rollout of smart cameras with enthusiasm or indifference, adopting the technology in their everyday life. Still, Chinese leaders have faced growing unhappiness over the widespread use of facial recognition.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-professor-files-rare-lawsuit-over-use-of-facial-recognition-technology-11572884626?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">In a rare lawsuit</a> over the technology in 2019, a Chinese law professor, Guo Bing, accused a zoo in the coastal city of Hangzhou of violating his consumer rights by requiring him to use a facial-recognition system to gain entrance to the zoo—and barring him when he didn&#39;t comply. The court ordered the zoo to pay damages to Guo and delete his data but left unaddressed whether it was legal for the zoo to continue to force visitors to undergo facial recognition.</p><p> A survey of public attitudes toward facial recognition in 2019 by the Nandu Personal Information Protection Research Center, a think tank in south China, also found regular Chinese were increasingly concerned their personal information was being leaked due to a lack of data security.</p><p> Tuesday&#39;s proposed regulation pulls together and fleshes out in one framework the restrictions on the use of face-recognition technology scattered throughout various laws in China, including in <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-set-to-pass-one-of-the-worlds-strictest-data-privacy-laws-11629201927?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">the national privacy law passed</a> in 2021. It states, for example, that facial data shouldn&#39;t be collected and used without consent, reiterating a key aspect of China&#39;s 2017 Cybersecurity Law, which requires individual consent for personal-data collection.</p><p> Part of this redundancy is practical: to make clear exactly how an existing law should be applied to the facial recognition context, Webster said. Through the rules, Beijing is also signaling that it is aware of the public concerns, Sacks said. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831492?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Facial recognition in China can be used for identification in malls, office buildings, airports and hotels.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Andy Wong/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Some provisions in the regulation go into granular detail, stating for example that facial recognition shouldn&#39;t be used in hotel rooms, bathrooms or toilets, places where the public has heavily pushed back on uses of the technology before. It also outlaws moves by entities to pressure individuals to adopt face recognition, such as in the case of the zoo, as a method to establish their identities.</p><p> At the same time, China, under its leader Xi Jinping, has been expanding its definition of national security to cover anything seen as undermining Communist Party rule, as Xi braces the country for a potential <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-congress-xi-jinping-us-11665753002" target="_blank" class="icon none">confrontation with the West</a> . In July, a revised and tightened <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinas-expanded-spy-law-adds-to-chilling-effect-of-detentions-ce8cea1a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">anti-espionage law</a> took effect, raising concerns among foreign governments and businesses.</p><p> The proposed regulation is the latest effort by authorities to walk the fine line between acknowledging public debate and maintaining tight control on the country&#39;s security. “It allows the government to have both a pressure valve release through showing the public that they&#39;re being responsive but also to deflect attention of the use of these technologies by central authorities,” Sacks said.</p><p> Write to Karen Hao at <a href="mailto:karen.hao@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">karen.hao@wsj.com</a> and Liza Lin at <a href="mailto:liza.lin@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">liza.lin@wsj.com</a></p></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 11:07:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-drafts-rules-for-facial-recognition-use-4953506e</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/china-drafts-rules-for-facial-recognition-use-4953506e<author><![CDATA[Karen HaoLiza Lin]]></author><category> Regulation/Government Policy</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Artificial Intelligence/Machine Learning</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>National/Public Security</category><category> Computer Science</category><category> Sciences/Humanities</category><category>国家安全措施/政策</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category>规定</category><category>government policy</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>artificial intelligence</category><category>机器学习</category><category>political</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>国家的</category><category>public security</category><category> computer science</category><category> sciences</category><category> humanities</category><category>国家安全措施</category><category>政策</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category></item><item><title><![CDATA[The Legal Assault on Corporate Diversity Efforts Has Begun]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Conservative groups challenge Amazon, Comcast and others using many of the same tools that helped kill affirmative-action programs in colleges <figure><img src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831356/?width=1278&amp;size=1" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><figcaption> Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal <span>Emil Lendof/The Wall Street Journal</span> </figcaption></figure><!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116214"></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116214"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> By <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/theo-francis" itemprop="url" rel="author">Theo Francis</a></span> and <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/lauren-weber" itemprop="url" rel="author">Lauren Weber</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1"> Aug. 8, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          bigtophero
"></div><p> Conservative legal activists <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">successfully challenged</a> the use of affirmative action by universities. Now they are going after diversity initiatives widely deployed across American corporations. Some companies are already reconsidering their efforts.</p><p> In lawsuits, shareholder letters and petitions to the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, activists are using some of the same tactics that progressive groups have used to advance diversity, equity and inclusion, or DEI, programs. They are arguing that companies are violating rules against race- and sex-discrimination, including those drawn from legislation designed to secure the rights of Black Americans.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/CMCSA" class="company-name">Comcast</a> settled a case accusing it of illegally favoring minority-owned small-business customers with grants and marketing advice. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/AMZN" class="company-name">Amazon</a> has been sued in Texas over a program offering an extra $10,000 to Black- or Latino-owned delivery-service contractors. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/SBUX" class="company-name">Starbucks</a> directors and executives are being sued by a shareholder arguing they violated their duty to investors by supporting diversity policies.</p><p> Dozens of corporate law firms and major employers have received letters from Republican officials warning them to adhere to laws prohibiting racial quotas and preferences in employment and contracting decisions.</p><p> Edward Blum, who also <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/affirmative-action-supreme-court-ed-blum-100b36c3" target="_blank" class="icon none">organized the challenge</a> that culminated in the US Supreme Court&#39;s decision to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/supreme-court-rules-against-affirmative-action-c94b5a9c?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">overturn affirmative action</a> , used a recently formed nonprofit group to sue Georgia investment manager Fearless Fund, charging that a grant program for startups is discriminatory. Fearless makes early-stage investments in businesses run by women of color.</p><p> Companies say their initiatives fall within the law. Many say they remain committed to increasing the demographic diversity of their workforces and suppliers, citing <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/the-business-case-for-more-diversity-11572091200" target="_blank" class="icon none">business benefits</a> and the hurdles some groups continue to face in American corporations.</p><p> Privately, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/companiesexpectnew-challenges-todiversitypolicies-after-court-ruling-4bf48c1d" target="_blank" class="icon none">many are asking their lawyers</a> if and how much they should modify their methods in light of the affirmative-action decision. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="841" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828205?width=1260&amp;height=841" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A federal lawsuit against Amazon.com targets a program awarding an additional $10,000 to Black, Latino and Native American delivery-service contractors to defray startup costs.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Kathy Tran/Bloomberg News</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Many of the legal efforts against corporate diversity programs predate the high court&#39;s June 29 decision.这项裁决主要针对高等教育招生，并未涉及就业或商业行为。</p><p> But it added momentum to an effort by conservative activists and public officials to challenge corporate diversity programs.长期以来，企业一直依赖类似于大学里支持平权行动的理由——多元化有好处。通过驳回这一理由，高等法院削弱了其他推广该理由的项目的理由。</p><p> “Anything a company&#39;s doing that is treating someone differently because of their race, even if it&#39;s a small part of the decision-making process, is going to be scrutinized,” said Dan Lennington, a former Wisconsin deputy solicitor general and deputy counsel for Wisconsin Institute for Law and Liberty, the legal group behind the Comcast lawsuit.</p><p> Employment lawyers say it is likely a matter of time before one of these cases reaches the Supreme Court. Some companies have decided they aren&#39;t going to wait for the court to weigh in. That is especially true for programs that were quickly adopted after the May 2020 killing of George Floyd in police custody, said Angela Berg, who led the global DEI practice at HR consulting firm Mercer and now consults independently.</p><p> Some executives “were uncomfortable with equity programs from the get-go,” said Berg, referring to initiatives such as mentorship or training programs. The Supreme Court has changed the risk calculation, she said.</p><p> Companies are evaluating diversity programs in light of litigation threats that often seem designed to stoke public fear, said Fordham University law professor Atinuke Adediran.她收到了大公司人力资源官员协会关于这个问题的询问。 “公司为多元化所做的大部分事情都是合法的，”她说。 “Companies may need to be ready to defend themselves.”</p><h3> <strong>A Civil War weapon</strong></h3><p> Cable giant Comcast limited a small-business grant program to companies at least 51% owned and operated by someone identifying as Black, indigenous, a person of color, or female—people the company said had been disproportionately affected by the coronavirus pandemic.</p><p> The Wisconsin Institute for Law and Liberty, in suing Comcast in April 2022, cited the 1866 Civil Rights Act.一项经常被称为第 1981 条的条款规定，所有美国人都应享有“与白人公民所享有的相同权利”，以起诉和执行合同。 The Wisconsin Institute, which says it supports litigation promoting “individual initiative and ordered liberty that leads to prosperity,” essentially turned that section on its head by gathering several white, male business owners as plaintiffs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="503" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831273?width=700&amp;height=503" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Some activists cite a Civil War-era law that says all Americans should have the same rights to sue and enforce contracts &#39;as is enjoyed by white citizens.&#39; Pictured is a sketch by F. Dielman showing a celebration of the abolition of slavery in the District of Columbia, April 1866.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Library of Congress</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In mid-September, when Comcast announced the next round of grants, it <a href="https://corporate.comcast.com/press/releases/comcast-rise-investment-fund-grants-small-businesses-covid-19-pandemic)" target="_blank" class="icon none">opened the program</a> to all small businesses. Two months later, Comcast settled the litigation.</p><p> A Comcast spokesman declined to comment. In a news release about the program in May, Comcast described the program as evolving “from helping businesses survive the pandemic, to helping businesses and their communities thrive with a focus on economic growth.”</p><p> A federal lawsuit against Amazon.com filed outside Dallas in July 2022 also invokes the 1866 law.它的目标是向黑人、拉丁裔和美洲原住民送货服务承包商额外奖励 10,000 美元，以支付启动成本。该诉讼还批评了亚马逊旨在帮助黑人企业在亚马逊网站上销售产品的计划。</p><p> The plaintiff, a Denton County, Texas, resident, wants to apply to start an Amazon delivery-service contractor, but says she won&#39;t until the company eliminates the assistance for minority contractors or offers whites and Asians the same benefit, the complaint says. The plaintiff can&#39;t apply to become an Amazon delivery service partner “without subjecting herself to racial discrimination,” the lawsuit says.</p><p> The case seeks class-action status.该诉讼由包括美国第一法律公司总法律顾问在内的律师提交，该法律公司是华盛顿特区的一家非盈利组织，由前特朗普政府顾问斯蒂芬·米勒领导。 America First Legal describes itself as combating “an unholy alliance of corrupt special interests, big tech titans, the fake news media, and liberal Washington politicians.”</p><p> Amazon has moved to dismiss the lawsuit, saying its selection process for delivery contractors is race-neutral and that the plaintiff doesn&#39;t have standing to sue because she hasn&#39;t applied to be an Amazon contractor.</p><p> In court filings, the company calls her complaint “the epitome of an abstract and generalized grievance by a member of the general population about an internal corporate program that has no actual effect on her.”</p><p> Amazon declined to comment on the lawsuit. “我们相信多样性、公平和包容性的重要性，”一位发言人在一份书面声明中表示。 “We&#39;ll investigate the potential impact of any legal decisions on our programs and adjust as necessary to comply with the law.”</p><h3> <strong>The workplace discrimination argument</strong></h3><p> Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 bans workplace discrimination.最近的平权行动决定并未直接涉及就业实践。但最高法院法官尼尔·戈萨奇在一致意见中指出，高等教育和就业法律中关于歧视的“实质上相同的语言”。</p><p> Starbucks officers and directors were sued in August 2022 by National Center for Public Policy Research, a conservative think tank that owns 56 shares in the coffee chain.它指控星巴克违反了《第七章》和第 1981 条，并指责星巴克官员在就业、供应商合同和高管薪酬等领域采取违反反歧视法的政策，从而违反了对股东的信托义务。</p><p> Under the policies, Starbucks says it wants at least 30% of its workforce at all levels to be Black, indigenous or people of color by 2025. It plans to implement an analytics tool that lets managers see their progress and uses workforce diversity measures to help set executive pay.</p><p> Starbucks and company officials are seeking to dismiss the case, with a hearing scheduled for Friday.他们表示，NCPPR 并未表现出这些政策造成任何真正的损害，这些政策受到一项法律原则的保护，该原则赋予公司官员在经营业务时拥有广泛的自由裁量权，而且法院也支持多元化政策。他们说，放弃它们将使星巴克容易受到其他诉讼的影响。 </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="884" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828201?width=1260&amp;height=884" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Starbucks officers and directors were sued last year over policies that involve increasing workforce diversity at all levels of the coffee chain.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Mario Tama/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “We remain committed to creating a culture of warmth and belonging, where everyone is welcome,” a company spokeswoman said.</p><p> In court, Starbucks and its officials also argue NCPPR doesn&#39;t represent shareholders, who have rejected previous proxy proposals from the group suggesting Starbucks favors liberal or “woke” perspectives.</p><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/KO" class="company-name">Coca-Cola</a> is among the companies that has already backtracked. 2021 年初，时任总法律顾问布拉德利·盖顿 (Bradley Gayton) 在致外部律师事务所的一封信中表示，这家汽水巨头 30% 的新法律工作应由女性、LGBTQ+、残疾人或少数种族和族裔群体成员的律师承担。信中称，律师事务所必须向可口可乐公司报告人口统计数据，如果不符合指导方针，可口可乐公司可能会降低费用。 Gayton stepped down from the role three months later.</p><p> American Civil Rights Project, a nonprofit law firm that also represents NCPPR in its Starbucks lawsuit, threatened to sue Coke on behalf of shareholders. In a letter to the company that June, the group called the policies “textbook violations” of Section 1981.</p><p> In early 2022 Gayton&#39;s successor, Monica Howard Doublas, wrote to the American Civil Rights Project that while the company remained fully committed to advancing DEI in the legal profession, she had contacted law firms to tell them the guidelines were never company policy.</p><h3> <strong>A chilling effect</strong></h3><p> America First Legal Foundation, the group backing the Texas lawsuit against Amazon, has written to the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, urging the four current commissioners to bypass the usual complaint process and open investigations into diversity practices at a range of brand-name companies.</p><p> Andrea Lucas, who was nominated to the commission by President Trump, declined to comment on the likelihood that she or other commissioners would open investigations.她表示，她认为许多企业多元化计划存在“重大法律和实际风险”。 “Equal opportunity is our charge,” she said of the agency&#39;s mission, “but the law does not demand equal outcomes.” </p><div class="media-object scope-
          wrap
"><figure class="media-object-image img-wrap"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="639" height="639" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-830072?width=639&amp;height=639" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Bradley Gayton, former general counsel at Coca-Cola, announced new guidelines for the makeup of attorneys doing legal work for the soda giant.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Coca-Cola/Business Wire</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> Civil-rights lawyers say conservative activists&#39; arguments distort the original purpose of laws designed to protect groups that, historically, have had fewer labor-market opportunities or difficulty cracking corporate ceilings.</p><p> “The intent here is more political gain and a chilling effect—unfortunately it&#39;s effective,” said Katy Youker, an attorney with the Lawyers&#39; Committee for Civil Rights Under Law, which has been tracking challenges to corporate programs.</p><p> In Florida, a federal judge last year halted enforcement of provisions in HB 7, better known as the Stop Woke Act, which would have restricted private employers from conducting some diversity-related training.法官表示，这些措施侵犯了公司的言论自由权。 Gov. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/ron-desantis">Ron DeSantis</a> &#39;s administration has appealed the decision.</p><p> The pressure leaves employers vulnerable to litigation for either going too far or not far enough in addressing barriers to equity and inclusion, lawyers say.</p><p> “Employers still have obligations to comply with civil rights statutes,” said Charles McLaurin, senior counsel with the NAACP Legal Defense and Educational Fund.他补充说，取消旨在扩大工作机会的 DEI 计划“有可能为某些边缘群体创造一个敌对的环境。 Companies would still face exposure.”</p><p> Write to Theo Francis at <a href="mailto:theo.francis@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">theo.francis@wsj.com</a> and Lauren Weber at <a href="mailto:Lauren.Weber@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">Lauren.Weber@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-
          bleed
"><figure class="media-object-image img-bleed"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="1260" height="840" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-828197?width=1260&amp;height=840" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> The administration of Florida Gov. Ron DeSantis appealed a federal judge&#39;s decision to halt enforcement of elements of what is known as the Stop Woke Act.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Daniel A. Varela/Miami Herald/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div></section></div></main></div> ]]>;</description><pubDate> Tue, 08 Aug 2023 09:30:00 GMT</pubDate><guid ispermalink="false"> https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173</guid><link/> https://www.wsj.com/articles/diversity-equity-dei-companies-blum-2040b173<author><![CDATA[Theo FrancisLauren Weber]]></author><category> WSJ公司</category><category>wsjillustration</category><category>领导者</category><category>Broadcasting</category><category> Cable Broadcasting</category><category>媒体/娱乐</category><category>Corporate Crime/Legal Action</category><category> Regulation/Government Policy</category><category> Labor/Personnel</category><category>企业/行业新闻</category><category>Workplace Discrimination/Abuse</category><category> Affirmative Action</category><category>政治/一般新闻</category><category>Society/Community</category><category>犯罪/法律诉讼</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>人权/公民自由</category><category>Social Issues</category><category> University/College</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法激活过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E Executive News Filter</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>SYND</category><category>华尔街日报-PRO-WSJ.com</category><category> corporate crime</category><category>合法举动</category><category>规定</category><category>government policy</category><category> labor</category><category>人员</category><category>公司的</category><category>行业新闻</category><category>workplace discrimination</category><category> abuse</category><category> affirmative action</category><category> political</category><category>一般新闻</category><category>society</category><category>社区</category><category>犯罪</category><category>歧视</category><category>教育</category><category>人权</category><category>公民权利</category><category>social issues</category><category> university</category><category> college</category><category>内容类型</category><category>法蒂瓦过滤器</category><category>C&amp;E 行政新闻过滤器</category><category>会展行业新闻过滤器</category><category>broadcasting</category><category> cable broadcasting</category><category>媒体</category><category>entertainment </category></item><item><title><![CDATA[Elon Musk Calls Cybertruck Tesla’s ‘Best Product Ever.’ Here Comes the Test.]]></title><description><![CDATA[<div> Truck is expected to hit the market by end of year, two years behind schedule <!-- data-module-name="article.app/lib/module/wsj/breadcrumbs" --><main id="main" role="main"><div class="wsj-article-headline-wrap crawler"></div><div class="articleLead" itemprop="articleLead" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116905"><div class="is-lead-inset"><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><div class="media-object-video"><div class="wsj-media-summary clearfix"><div class="strap-container"><h4 class="strap" itemprop="description"></h4></div></div><iframe width="400" height="225" src="https://video-api.wsj.com/api-video/player/v3/iframe.html?guid=B1A79903-5C46-4C69-8AC4-A0082045E182&amp;height=225&amp;width=400&amp;plid=video_amp&amp;chainVideos=true&amp;parentUrl=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.wsj.com%2Famp%2Farticles%2Felon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45&amp;a=a" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></iframe><p class="imageCaption"> The launch of Tesla&#39;s Cybertruck is one of the most anticipated EV releases in history. Barclays analyst Dan Levy and AlixPartners&#39; Mark Wakefield weigh in on how Tesla&#39;s first pickup could shake up the pickup market. Photo: Frederic Brown/Getty Images<span class="imageCredit">
        
        
        </span></p></div></div></div></div><div class="articleBody" data-sbid="WP-WSJ-0001116905"><div class="clearfix bylineWrap"><div class="byline"> <span class="author" itemprop="name"><a href="https://www.wsj.com/news/author/rebecca-elliott" itemprop="url" rel="author">丽贝卡·埃利奥特</a></span></div><time class="timestamp article__timestamp flexbox__flex--1">Aug. 8, 2023 5:30 am ET </time></div><div subscriptions-actions="" subscriptions-display="NOT data.noSharing"><div class="share-bar"><amp-social-share type="system" width="72" height="24" data-param-url="https://www.wsj.com/articles/elon-musk-calls-cybertruck-teslas-best-product-ever-here-comes-the-test-42095f45"></amp-social-share></div></div><section subscriptions-section="content"><p> <a href="https://www.wsj.com/topics/person/elon-musk">Elon Musk</a> is seeking to reimagine the classic American pickup with the Cybertruck, a distinctive-looking truck that is all angles and unpainted stainless steel.</p><p> Now, with <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TSLA" class="company-name">Tesla</a> expected to debut the truck by the end of the year, the coming months will test whether he can execute on that vision and deliver the company&#39;s first new passenger vehicle in more than three years.</p><p> Bringing the Cybertruck to market has already proven challenging, with years of delays that have included design changes, cost overruns and pandemic uncertainties. The latest twist came Monday when the electric-car maker announced Zach Kirkhorn, who played an important role in keeping company costs in line as CFO, <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-finance-chief-zach-kirkhorn-steps-down-44e00ad?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">had stepped down</a> .</p><p> The electric truck was designed to break the mold of a traditional pickup, with a triangular profile and the <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-unveiled-a-bullet-proof-pickup-then-the-window-broke-11574444427?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">promise of a bulletproof body</a> . Some industry observers worry the uniquely designed vehicle will have limited appeal to buyers and that the costs of beginning production will hurt profitability as margins are <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q2-earnings-report-2023-9be2b571?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">already under pressure</a> .</p><p> Investors are betting the truck will be worth the wait, and that it will inject new excitement into the Tesla brand, which has an older line up than many of its competitors.</p><p> “The Cybertruck is so different, it&#39;ll jazz up the entire franchise,” said Gary Black, managing partner of the Future Fund, a Tesla investor.</p><p> Musk has been hyping the truck for years. He has called it the company&#39;s “best product ever” and has pitched the vehicle as a “badass, futuristic armored personnel carrier” that accelerates like a sports car and is packed with new technology. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="466" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831285?width=700&amp;height=466" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> Tesla has taken on manufacturing challenges with the Cybertruck, which uses stronger, heavier stainless steel instead of the sheet metal typically used in car bodies.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Robyn Beck/Agence France-Presse/Getty Images</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> In April, Musk said Tesla likely would begin <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q1-earnings-report-2023-6b441d30?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">delivering the new pickups</a> in small numbers by the end of September. Output is expected to climb in 2024.</p><p> During the company&#39;s most recent call with Wall Street analysts, however, Musk sidestepped a question about pricing and delivery schedules. Instead, he said deliveries would come this year. He also echoed past warnings that beginning production of a new vehicle can be tricky.</p><p> “The production ramp will move as fast as the slowest and least lucky elements of the entire supply chain and internal production,” Musk said last month.</p><p> Tesla didn&#39;t respond to requests for comment.</p><p> Ramping up production of new vehicles has bedeviled Tesla, where Musk has described the launch of the Model 3 sedan several years ago as “production hell” that nearly killed the company.</p><p> Originally expected in 2021, the Cybertruck began to face challenges almost as soon as it was first shown in November 2019.</p><p> Within months, the Covid-19 pandemic was wreaking havoc on global supply chains and the Cybertruck took a back seat to surer bets designed to <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-tsla-q4-earnings-report-2021-11643162910?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">quickly expand Tesla&#39;s market share</a> or <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-to-introduce-upgraded-model-s-to-jump-start-high-end-model-sales-11623334024?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">pad the bottom line</a> , people familiar with the matter said.</p><p> Later, as employees turned their attention to the Cybertruck, they struggled to deliver on their boss&#39;s promises while keeping a lid on costs. </p><div class="media-object scope-
          inline
"><figure class="media-object-image img-inline"><div class="image-container responsive-media"><img width="700" height="412" src="https://images.wsj.net/im-831286?width=700&amp;height=412" alt="" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"></div><figcaption class="imageCaption"><p class="imageCaptionContent"> A Model Y on the factory floor at Tesla&#39;s &#39;Cyber Rodeo&#39; marking the opening last year of the company&#39;s factory outside of Austin, Texas.</p><p class="imageCredit"> Photo: Jay Janner/Associated Press</p></figcaption></figure></div><p> “You can make something infinitely desirable, but if it&#39;s not affordable, that will constrain people&#39;s ability to buy it because they don&#39;t have the money,” Musk said in January 2022, adding that he worried about making a truck that was within reach for Tesla&#39;s customers.</p><p> He initially promised <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/tesla-targets-u-s-auto-makers-profit-engine-with-electric-pickup-11574341200?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">three tiers of the truck</a> , starting with a $39,900 entry-level model and topping out at a higher-end version starting at $69,900. He has since said the pricing and specs would be different, citing inflation and “various issues” without sharing specifics.</p><p> The company has taken on an array of new manufacturing challenges with the Cybertruck, which uses stronger, heavier stainless steel instead of the sheet metal typically used in car bodies.</p><p> Tesla aimed to skip an expensive manufacturing step for the outer shell of the truck with stainless steel, which doesn&#39;t need to be painted because it is corrosion-resistant. However, it is rarely used to form vehicle bodies in part because it is less malleable than traditional materials. (DeLorean Motor&#39;s stainless-steel-bodied sports car was featured as the time machine in the “Back to the Future” films.)</p><p> “There&#39;s not industrywide knowledge of how to build stainless steel vehicles, and so there&#39;s a whole bunch of things nobody knows about that they&#39;re going to encounter,” said Doug Betts, president of JD Power&#39;s automotive division.</p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
          wrap
"></div><p> And while Tesla excels in areas such as software and powertrain development, it has struggled with the process of building the car body, something the Cybertruck is likely to test, Betts said.</p><p> In addition to reimagining how pickup trucks should look, Musk wanted to upend how they are assembled. He envisioned a vehicle whose outer walls provide much of the overall structure.</p><p> “We moved the mass to the outside. We created an exoskeleton,” Musk said at the 2019 reveal.</p><p> However, Tesla has scaled back its exoskeleton ambitions, pursuing a more traditional vehicle design with an interior structure, people familiar with the matter said. The company did so, at least in part, to meet safety standards, one of the people said.</p><p> Some auto observers had expected more.</p><p> “It&#39;s unconventional in some areas, but for the most part it&#39;s a conventional build,” said Sandy Munro, an engineering consultant who tears apart cars and has reviewed pictures of early versions of the Cybertruck. “It&#39;s not the dramatic change that I was looking forward to,” he said, adding that he still thinks the vehicle will “take the market by storm.”</p><p> Musk has said he expects to make 250,000 or more Cybertrucks a year once output ramps up, making it a niche product in comparison to the company&#39;s best selling Model Y crossover. In total, Tesla sold about 1.3 million vehicles last year and is aiming to sell 20 million annually by 2030.</p><p> The Cybertruck&#39;s delays put it behind in a competitive segment where rivals have already brought their own EV pickups to market. <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/F" class="">Ford Motor</a> <span class="company-name-type">&#39;s</span> F-150 Lightning, the top-selling electric pickup, starts at $49,995 after the company <a href="https://www.wsj.com/articles/ford-cuts-price-of-ev-f-150-lightning-truck-by-up-to-17-2cc21c6a?mod=article_inline" target="_blank" class="icon none">slashed prices last month</a> . Rivian Automotive&#39;s competitor, the R1T, starts at $73,000.</p><div class="media-object scope-web
          wrap
"><div class="media-object-rich-text"><h4>分享你的意见</h4><p><em>Do you think Tesla&#39;s Cybertruck will ultimately be successful?为什么或者为什么不？加入下面的对话。</em></p></div></div><p> Still, if Tesla can be successful, there is great potential. Full-size pickup trucks are the cash cow of the US auto industry, making up 13% of North American vehicle sales last year while being responsible for about 40% of profits, according to Wells Fargo.</p><p> Analysts expect early efforts to build Tesla&#39;s truck could further erode the company&#39;s profitability.</p><p> But the truck should eventually boost Tesla&#39;s profit margin if the company is able to deliver on its promises, said Anthony Wang, who co-leads the technology investing team at <a href="https://www.wsj.com/market-data/quotes/TROW" class="">T. Rowe Price Associates</a> <span class="company-name-type">,</span> one of the company&#39;s largest shareholders.</p><p> “Whether the ramp comes this quarter or next, it doesn&#39;t really matter,” Wang said. “What matters more is: Can they execute on the cost and the specs?”</p><p>写信给丽贝卡·埃利奥特（Rebecca Elliott）： <a href="mailto:rebecca.elliott@wsj.com" target="_blank" class="icon ">rebecca.elliott@wsj.com</a> </p><div class="media-object scope-web|mobileapps
